Preprocessing¶

Lets load the fresh dataset again. A lot of the data preprocessing seems to have been done already but let's see if we can do some feature engineering

In [25]:

Split the data into training and testing data. Using 20% of the data for testing

By checking linear correlations, we can see that temperature, hour and humidity seem to be the most important fields correlating to the number of bikes used. Temperature and humidity seems to be more important for casual users than registered users, while the hour seems to be correlating more with registered users than casual users

In [35]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
In [36]:
class DataFrameSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, attribute_names):
        self.attribute_names = attribute_names
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    def transform(self, X):
        return X[self.attribute_names].values
In [37]:
attribs = ['temp', 'atemp', 'hr', 'yr', 'season', 'windspeed', 'mnth', 'workingday', 'weekday', 'holiday', 'weathersit', 'hum']
full_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('selector', DataFrameSelector(attribs)),
    ])

In [45]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

param_grid = [
    {'n_estimators': [3, 5, 30], 'max_features': [2, 4, 6, 8]},
    {'bootstrap': [False], 'n_estimators': [3, 10], 'max_features': [2, 3, 4]},
]

Final random forest regressor model is below and it has a root mean squared error of around 43 bikes per hour on the test set

In [56]:
final_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

X_test = full_pipeline.fit_transform(test_set)
y_test = test_set['cnt'].values

final_predictions = final_model.predict(X_test)

final_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, final_predictions)
final_rmse = np.sqrt(final_mse)

print(final_rmse)

43.0431639417
